I’d need to see your code to be specific, ideally as a link to github (or similar).

That said, you have a few errors, all related to function arguments.

wusti:

C:\Users\mustafa akba■\Documents\em1\src\main\java\frc\robot\subsystems\Swerve.java:29: error: no suitable constructor found for SwerveDriveOdometry(SwerveDriveKinematics,Rotation2d)
swerveOdometry = new SwerveDriveOdometry(Constants.Swerve.swerveKinematics, getYaw());
^

This is saying that you’re trying to construct a SwerveDriveOdometry object on line 29 of Swerve.java by passing in a SwerveDriveKinematics object (from a constant) and a Rotation2d object (result of your getYaw method), but the SwerveDriveOdometry class does not define a constructor that accepts only those 2 specific objects. You’ll need to look at what constructors are defined and ensure you’re passing in the correct arguments in the correct order. The next few lines tell you what the possible constructor argument lists are.

wusti:

C:\Users\mustafa akba■\Documents\em1\src\main\java\frc\robot\subsystems\Swerve.java:72: error: incompatible types: Pose2d cannot be converted to Rotation2d
swerveOdometry.resetPosition(pose, getYaw());
^
C:\Users\mustafa akba■\Documents\em1\src\main\java\frc\robot\subsystems\Swerve.java:95: error: incompatible types: SwerveModuleState cannot be converted to SwerveModulePosition
swerveOdometry.update(getYaw(), getStates());
^

These 2 are telling you are passing the wrong type of object into the listed methods. Specifically a Rotation2d object instead of a Pose2d object for the first, and a SwerveModuleState object instead of a SwerveModulePosition object for the second.

wusti:

C:\Users\mustafa akba■\Documents\em1\src\main\java\frc\robot\RobotContainer.java:49: error: cannot find symbol
() → robotCentric.get()));
^
symbol: method get()
location: variable robotCentric of type JoystickButton

This says youre trying to call a method that is not defined for the JoystickButton class.

Given these errors, I’m going to assume this code was copied from somewhere, not something you wrote yourself. I’d also wager that what you copied from used an older version of wpilib, and certain APIs have since changed.

If this is the case, I highly recommend finding a different project to start from. There are many examples posted here on CD of other teams attempting swerve and sharing their code, or you can use a framework such as YAGSL to build on top of.
